>
	<p>Old Orchard Beach is seven miles of white sand, a wooden pier extending into the Atlantic, and a summer energy unlike anywhere else in New England. Every year from Memorial Day through Labor Day, the town transforms — crowds arrive from across the country and from Quebec, rides open on the beach, fireworks launch every Thursday night, and the pier fills with the smell of fried dough and salt air.</p>

	<p>Here's what's happening at Old Orchard Beach in summer 2026, and how to make the most of your visit from Saco Bay Hotel — less than two miles away.</p>

	<h2>What's New for 2026</h2>

	<p>Palace Playland is adding a brand-new <strong>Speedy Coaster</strong> for the 2026 season — described as "packed with smooth twists, playful hills, and nonstop excitement." It joins the three rides that debuted in 2025: Nitro Speed, Wind Surfer, and the Balloon Ride.</p>

	<p>Downtown, <strong>The Local OOB</strong> opened in late 2025 at 23 Washington Ave — a year-round spot with upscale bar food, pizza, and seafood that's already drawing regulars. The Seaside Pavilion announces its summer concert schedule each spring (box office opens in May); their 2026 lineup will be posted at seasidepavilion.org.</p>

	<h2>Thursday Night Fireworks</h2>

	<p>The weekly fireworks are the anchor of any summer visit. Every Thursday night from late June through late August, professional fireworks launch from the beach near the Pier and Palace Playland at approximately <strong>9:45 PM</strong>. They're free, visible from anywhere on the main beach, and genuinely impressive — full professional shows, not sparklers.</p>

	<p>The season typically runs late June through late August (historically June 24 through August 26). Confirm exact dates at oobmaine.com before you visit. <strong>July 4, 2026 falls on a Saturday</strong>, which means Thursday night fireworks land on July 2 — giving guests who arrive mid-week a fireworks doubleheader.</p>

	<h2>Rock the Park: Summer Concert Series</h2>

	<p>The Old Orchard Beach Recreation Department runs a free outdoor concert series at <strong>The Ballpark, 7 Ballpark Way</strong>. Gates open at 5 PM; music runs 6–8 PM. Parking is free. The 2025 season featured seven concerts — all tribute acts, including Queen, Elton John, Bruce Springsteen, and Taylor Swift tributes. The 2026 schedule will be posted at oldorchardbeachme.myrec.com; expect a similar format.</p>

	<h2>Seaside Pavilion Concert Series</h2>

	<p>The Seaside Pavilion at 8 Sixth Street is a covered outdoor venue with stadium seating, built in 1998 on a site with roots going back to 1885. Each summer it programs a mix of symphony performances, tribute acts, Christian artists, and community events. The 195th Army National Guard Band performs a free patriotic concert there every July 4 at 7 PM. Check seasidepavilion.org for the 2026 lineup.</p>

	<h2>OOB Pier Festival</h2>

	<p>Produced by The Salvation Army in some form for nearly 100 years, the Pier Festival is a free four-night event (typically late July) running 7–10 PM. Giveaways, balloon animals, face painting, music, and dancing. The 2025 dates were July 24–27 — expect similar timing in 2026.</p>

	<h2>Beach Olympics</h2>

	<p>The Annual Old Orchard Beach Olympics — a three-day event held in mid-August — brings athletic competitions, music, and displays to Town Square and Palace Playland, with proceeds benefiting Special Olympics Maine. The 2025 edition was the 36th annual, held August 16–18.</p>

	<h2>Ocean Park Events</h2>

	<p>Ocean Park is the small Victorian community directly adjacent to Old Orchard Beach. On July 4, the <strong>Ocean Park Independence Day Parade</strong> sets off at 10 AM from Temple Ave. at the Bell Tower. A few days prior, the <strong>Ocean Park Sand Sculpture Contest</strong> draws families to the beach (typically July 3).</p>

	<h2>September Car Show</h2>

	<p>One of New England's largest car shows takes place in September — the 32nd Annual edition expected in 2026, typically held on a mid-September weekend at the Chamber of Commerce on First Street. Muscle cars, hot rods, antiques, and rare builds fill the lot from 6 AM to 3 PM.</p>

	<h2>Best Months to Visit</h2>

	<p><strong>July and August</strong> are peak season — everything is open, fireworks launch weekly, and the beach is at full energy. July is the driest month (roughly three inches of rain for the entire month) with average highs of 76–78°F.</p>

	<p><strong>Late June</strong> offers most of the summer experience with smaller crowds and slightly lower prices. <strong>September</strong> is the sleeper pick: water is often warmer than July (it retains summer heat), crowds thin after Labor Day, most restaurants stay open, and hotel rates drop significantly. The car show and a few other events keep September worth visiting.</p>

	<h2>The French-Canadian Connection</h2>

	<p>An estimated 30–40% of Old Orchard Beach's summer visitors are Canadian, primarily from Quebec. This connection dates to 1853, when the Grand Trunk Railroad opened from Montreal. OOB is the closest Atlantic beach to Quebec City and Montreal. Bilingual signage, French menus, and French-speaking staff are common throughout downtown. The Canadian flag flies outside many properties on the strip.</p>

	<h2>Parking Tips</h2>

	<p>Paid parking runs from May 1 through Labor Day at <strong>$3/hour</strong> at municipal kiosks downtown. On summer weekends, lots fill fast — by mid-afternoon on busy Saturdays, all convenient spots are gone. Arrive early. The <strong>Milliken Street lot</strong> is a local tip — steps from the beach, less congested than the main lots, and an easy 10-minute walk to the pier.</p>

	<p>The easiest solution: stay at Saco Bay Hotel in Saco and drive in for specific events rather than leaving your car all day. Most summer mornings, you can park, enjoy the beach, and return before the afternoon rush.</p>

	<div class="tip-box">
		<strong>Local Tip</strong>
		<p>For the Thursday night fireworks, drive in by 7 PM and walk straight to the beach near the pier. You don't need to be on the pier itself — any open stretch of sand between the pier and the Milliken Street area gives you a clear sightline. Bring a blanket; evening temperatures drop to the low 60s.</p>
	</div>
